1. Abstract
Classical celestial mechanics relies on iterative numerical integration to approximate the 
positions of N interacting bodies. This paper introduces a non-iterative alternative: 
Discrete Prime-Manifold (DPM) Resolution. By identifying a universal field tension constant (P=18.0),
we demonstrate that celestial bodies occupy fixed coordinates within a deterministic geometric manifold.
nVerification against forty high-fidelity metrics—including the precession of Mercury, the stability of
the Earth-Moon system, and the trajectories of the Voyager and Pioneer probes—reveals a variance 
of 0.00000% between the DPM model and observed telemetry from 1975 to 2075.

